linSvm1 <- ksvm(V3 ~ V2 + V1, 
                data = ex6data1, 
                C = 1,
                type = "C-svc",
                kernel = "vanilladot", 
                kpar = list(),
                scaled = F)
plot(linSvm1, data = as.data.frame(ex6data1))

decisionBoundary <- function(svm){
    w <- colSums(coef(svm)[[1]] * ex6data1[unlist(alphaindex(svm)), 2:1])
    b <- b(svm)
    C <- param(svm)[[1]]
    return(list(slope = -w[2]/w[1], intcpt = b/w[1], C = C))
}
bound1 <- decisionBoundary(linSvm1)
g2 <- g1 + geom_abline(intercept = bound1$intcpt, slope = bound1$slope, color = 2)
g2

linSvm2 <- ksvm(V3 ~ V2 + V1,
                data = ex6data1,
                C = 100,
                type = "C-svc",
                kernel = "vanilladot", 
                kpar = list(),
                scaled = F)

bound2 <- decisionBoundary(linSvm2)
g3 <- g2 + geom_abline(intercept = bound2$intcpt, slope = bound2$slope, color = 3)
g3

1.2 SVM with Gaussian Kernels

1.2.1 Gaussian Kernel

gkGenerator <- function (sigma = 1) {
    gk <- function(Xi, Xj = NULL) {
        normSquared <- sum((Xi - Xj) ^ 2)
        # I'm not sure this needs to be coerced to a matrix, but rbfdot returns
        # a 1x1 matrix, so when in Rome...
        return(as.matrix(exp(-normSquared / (2 * sigma ^ 2))))
    }
    return(new("rbfkernel", .Data = gk, kpar = list(sigma = sigma)))
}

Because the built-in Gaussian kernel function in kernlab takes a different sigma parameter, I’ve defined a function that will make it comparable to the way it’s calculated in the assignment.

sigTransform <- function(sigma){
    1 / (2 * sigma ^ 2)
}
x1 <- c(1, 2, 1)
x2 = c(0, 4, -1)
sigma = 2
gk <- gkGenerator(sigma)
gk(x1, x2)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.3246525
rbf <- rbfdot(sigTransform(sigma))
rbf(x1, x2)
##           [,1]
## [1,] 0.3246525

This should be about 0.324652. For good measure, I also checked the value using the rbfdot function built into kernlab.

                data = ex6data2,
                C = 1,
                type = "C-svc",
                kernel = gkGenerator, 
                kpar = list(sigma = sigTransform(0.1)),
                scaled = F)
